To see why, we can use set theoretical notation to represent the sets of "hurricanes", "storms", and "destructive storms":

- hurricanes = {H1, H2, H3,...}
- storms = {S1, S2, S3,...}
- destructive storms ≠ {D1, D2, D3,...}

The statement then translates to:

∀x(Hx ∈ storms) ∧ ∃x(Sx ∈ destructive storms)

which is true, as all hurricanes are storms, but there is no guarantee that any hurricanes are also part of the set of destructive storms.

Therefore, the conclusion "some hurricanes are destructive" is not necessarily true, and the statement is false.

